This executive order, issued on May 14, 2020, by President Donald Trump, aims to expand domestic production of strategic resources necessary to respond to the COVID-19 outbreak. The order delegates authority to the Chief Executive Officer of the United States International Development Finance Corporation (DFC) to make loans and take additional actions to create, maintain, protect, expand, and restore domestic industrial base capabilities and supply chains needed for the COVID-19 response. The order specifies that the loan authority is limited to loans that support the national response and recovery to COVID-19 or the resiliency of domestic supply chains. The order also outlines that loans must comply with relevant guidelines and regulations. The delegation of authority in this order will expire after a 2-year period or upon termination of certain requirements described in the Act. The order states that it does not impair existing authority granted by law to executive departments or agencies or the functions of the Director of the Office of Management and Budget. It also clarifies that the order does not create any enforceable rights or benefits against the United States or any other party.